Model Calibration, Validation, and Uncertainty Analysis
This implies that it is important to:


Select appropriate parameter values (model calibration);
Make sure that the calibrated model is capturing key dynamics (model validation);
Account for uncertainty in the parameter estimates and projections (uncertainty analysis)

Why is Hand-Tuning Problematic?
This representation shows where hand-tuning can fall short:


Assumptions about the discrepancy and error are not made explicit;
Assumptions about discrepancy and error may not be applied consistently;
The errors in the data collection process may be large, and neglecting discrepancy and error may result in overfitting to just one realization.


As a result, we will focus on statistical calibration.

Key Points

Assigning probabilities to deeply uncertain outcomes should be done carefully;
Avoiding this doesn’t solve any problems (and may create more!)

Key Points

We look at the specific example of future CO2 emissions;
Probabilistic analyses help us understand the drivers of future emissions and impact of joint emissions-geophysical uncertainties.
